THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF MICHIGAN ENACT:
1 Sec. 3. (1) "Average daily attendance", for the purposes of
2 complying with federal law, means 92% of the pupils counted in
3 membership on the pupil membership count day, as defined in section
4 6(7).
5 (2) "Board" means the governing body of a district or public
6 school academy.
7 (3) "Center" means the center for educational performance and
8 information created in section 94a.
CRM S01533'25 (S-3) CR-1 mposkv

4
1 (4) "Community district" means a school district organized
2 under part 5b of the revised school code, MCL 380.381 to 380.396.
3 (5) "Cooperative education program" means a written voluntary
4 agreement between and among districts to provide certain
5 educational programs for pupils in certain groups of districts. The
6 written agreement must be approved by all affected districts at
7 least annually and must specify the educational programs to be
8 provided and the estimated number of pupils from each district who
9 will participate in the educational programs.
10 (6) "Department", except as otherwise provided in this
11 article, means the department of education.
12 (7) "District" means, except as otherwise specifically
13 provided in this act, a local school district established under the
14 revised school code or, except in sections 6(4), 6(6), 11x, 11y,
15 11aa, 12c, 13, 20, 22a, 22p, 27l, 31a, 51a(14), 105, 105c, and 166b,
16 a public school academy. Except in section 20, district also
17 includes a community district.
18 (8) "District of residence", except as otherwise provided in
19 this subsection, means the district in which a pupil's custodial
20 parent or parents or legal guardian resides. For a pupil described
21 in section 24b, the pupil's district of residence is the district
22 in which the pupil enrolls under that section. For a pupil
23 described in section 6(4)(d), the pupil's district of residence is
24 considered to be the district or intermediate district in which the
25 pupil is counted in membership under that section. For a pupil
26 under court jurisdiction who is placed outside the district in
27 which the pupil's custodial parent or parents or legal guardian
28 resides, the pupil's district of residence is considered to be the
29 educating district or educating intermediate district.
CRM S01533'25 (S-3) CR-1 mposkv

5
1 (9) "District superintendent" means the superintendent of a
2 district or the chief administrator of a public school academy.
3 Sec. 6. (1) "Center program" means a program operated by a
4 district or by an intermediate district for special education
5 pupils from several districts in programs for pupils with autism
6 spectrum disorder, pupils with severe cognitive impairment, pupils
7 with moderate cognitive impairment, pupils with severe multiple
8 impairments, pupils with hearing impairment, pupils with visual
9 impairment, and pupils with physical impairment or other health
10 impairment. Programs for pupils with emotional impairment housed in
11 buildings that do not serve regular education pupils also qualify.
12 Unless otherwise approved by the department, a center program
13 either serves all constituent districts within an intermediate
14 district or serves several districts with less than 50% of the
15 pupils residing in the operating district. In addition, special
16 education center program pupils placed part-time in noncenter
17 programs to comply with the least restrictive environment
18 provisions of section 1412 of the individuals with disabilities
19 education act, 20 USC 1412, may be considered center program pupils
20 for pupil accounting purposes for the time scheduled in either a
21 center program or a noncenter program.
22 (2) "District and high school graduation rate" means the
23 annual completion and pupil dropout rate that is calculated by the
24 center pursuant to nationally recognized standards.
25 (3) "District and high school graduation report" means a
26 report of the number of pupils, excluding adult education
27 participants, in the district for the immediately preceding school
28 year, adjusted for those pupils who have transferred into or out of
29 the district or high school, who leave high school with a diploma
CRM S01533'25 (S-3) CR-1 mposkv

6
1 or other credential of equal status.
2 (4) "Membership", except as otherwise provided in this
3 article, means for a district, a public school academy, or an
4 intermediate district the sum of the product of .90 times the
5 number of full-time equated pupils in grades K to 12 actually
6 enrolled and in regular daily attendance in the district, public
7 school academy, or intermediate district on the pupil membership
8 count day for the current school year, plus the product of .10
9 times the final audited count from the supplemental count day of
10 full-time equated pupils in grades K to 12 actually enrolled and in
11 regular daily attendance in the district, public school academy, or
12 intermediate district for the immediately preceding school year. A
13 district's, public school academy's, or intermediate district's
14 membership is adjusted as provided under section 25e for pupils who
15 enroll after the pupil membership count day in a strict discipline
16 academy operating under sections 1311b to 1311m of the revised
17 school code, MCL 380.1311b to 380.1311m. All pupil counts used in
18 this subsection are as determined by the department and calculated
19 by adding the number of pupils registered for attendance plus
20 pupils received by transfer and minus pupils lost as defined by
21 rules promulgated by the superintendent, and as corrected by a
22 subsequent department audit. The amount of the foundation allowance
23 for a pupil in membership is determined under section 20. In making
24 the calculation of membership, all of the following, as applicable,
25 apply to determining the membership of a district, a public school
26 academy, or an intermediate district:
27 (a) Except as otherwise provided in this subsection, and
28 pursuant to subsection (6), a pupil is counted in membership in the
29 pupil's educating district or districts. Except as otherwise
CRM S01533'25 (S-3) CR-1 mposkv

7
1 provided in this subsection, an individual pupil must not be
2 counted for more than a total of 1.0 full-time equated membership.
3 (b) If a pupil is educated in a district other than the
4 pupil's district of residence, if the pupil is not being educated
5 as part of a cooperative education program, if the pupil's district
6 of residence does not give the educating district its approval to
7 count the pupil in membership in the educating district, and if the
8 pupil is not covered by an exception specified in subsection (6) to
9 the requirement that the educating district must have the approval
10 of the pupil's district of residence to count the pupil in
11 membership, the pupil is not counted in membership in any district.
12 (c) A special education pupil educated by the intermediate
13 district is counted in membership in the intermediate district.
14 (d) A pupil placed by a court or state agency in an on-grounds
15 program of a juvenile detention facility, a child caring
16 institution, or a mental health institution, or a pupil funded
17 under section 53a, is counted in membership in the district or
18 intermediate district approved by the department to operate the
19 program.
20 (e) A pupil enrolled in the Michigan Schools for the Deaf and
21 Blind is counted in membership in the pupil's intermediate district
22 of residence.
23 (f) A pupil enrolled in a career and technical education
24 program supported by a millage levied over an area larger than a
25 single district or in an area vocational-technical education
26 program established under section 690 of the revised school code,
27 MCL 380.690, is counted in membership only in the pupil's district
28 of residence.
29 (g) A pupil enrolled in a public school academy is counted in
CRM S01533'25 (S-3) CR-1 mposkv

8
1 membership in the public school academy.
2 (h) For the purposes of this section and section 6a, for a
3 cyber school, as that term is defined in section 551 of the revised
4 school code, MCL 380.551, that is in compliance with section 553a
5 of the revised school code, MCL 380.553a, a pupil's participation
6 in the cyber school's educational program is considered regular
7 daily attendance, and for a district or public school academy, a
8 pupil's participation in a virtual course as that term is defined
9 in section 21f is considered regular daily attendance. Beginning
10 July 1, 2021, this subdivision is subject to section 8c. It is the
11 intent of the legislature that the immediately preceding sentence
12 apply retroactively and is effective July 1, 2021. For the purposes
13 of this subdivision, for a pupil enrolled in a cyber school, all of
14 the following apply with regard to the participation requirement as
15 described in this subdivision:
16 (i) Except as otherwise provided in this subdivision, the pupil
17 shall participate in each scheduled course on pupil membership
18 count day or supplemental count day, as applicable. If the pupil is
19 absent on pupil membership count day or supplemental count day, as
