1 (17) (15) Each grant recipient shall enroll children
2 identified under subsection (8)(b) according to how far the child's
3 household income is below 400% of the federal poverty guidelines by
4 ranking each applicant child's household income from lowest to
5 highest and dividing the applicant children into quintiles based on
6 how far the child's household income is below 400% of the federal
7 poverty guidelines, and then enrolling children in the quintile
8 with the lowest household income before enrolling children in the
9 quintile with the next lowest household income until slots are
10 completely filled. If the grant recipient determines that all
11 eligible children are being served and that there are no children
12 on the waiting list who live with families with a household income
13 that is equal to or less than 400% of the federal poverty
14 guidelines, the grant recipient may then enroll children who live
15 with families with a household income that is greater than 400% of
16 the federal poverty guidelines. The enrollment process must
17 consider income and risk factors, such that children determined
18 with higher need are enrolled before children with lesser need. For
19 purposes of this subsection, all age-eligible children served in
20 foster care or who are experiencing homelessness or who have
21 individualized education programs recommending placement in an
22 inclusive preschool setting are considered to live with families
23 with household income equal to or less than 400% of the federal
24 poverty guidelines regardless of actual family income and are
25 prioritized for enrollment within the lowest quintile. This
26 subsection does not apply after September 30, 2025.
