5 Sec. 164l. (1) Not later than 30 days after the enactment of
6 the amendatory act that added this section, the legislature shall
7 provide to the responsible entity and the state budget director a
8 list of legislatively directed spending items, which may be
9 referred to in this section as grants or direct appropriation
10 grants, funded under the amendatory act that added this section
11 consistent with house or senate rules and this section. The list
12 must include all information and documents pertaining to the funded
13 items as publicly disclosed in accordance with house or senate
14 rules and this section.
15 (2) Notwithstanding any other conditions or requirements for
16 direct appropriation grants, the responsible entity shall perform,
17 at a minimum, at least all of the following activities to
18 administer the grants described in subsection (1):
19 (a) Establish a process to review, complete, and execute a
20 grant agreement with a grant recipient. The responsible entity
21 shall not execute a grant agreement unless all necessary
22 documentation has been submitted and reviewed.
23 (b) Verify to the extent possible that a grant recipient is a
24 not-for-profit entity and will use funds as publicly disclosed and
25 for a public purpose that serves the economic prosperity, health,
26 safety, or general welfare of the residents of this state.
27 (c) Review and verify all necessary information to ensure the
28 grant recipient is reasonably able to execute the grant agreement,
29 perform its fiduciary duty, and comply with all applicable state
CRM S01533'25 (S-3) CR-1 mposkv

399
1 and federal statutes. The responsible entity may deduct the cost of
2 background checks and any other efforts performed as part of this
3 verification from the amount of the designated grant award.
4 (d) Disburse the grant money per the grant disbursement
5 schedule in the executed grant agreement on a reimbursement basis
6 after the grantee has provided sufficient documentation, as
7 determined by the responsible entity, to verify that expenditures
8 were made in accordance with the project purpose.
9 (e) If the state budget director determines that information
10 provided by the grantee does not meet the disclosure requirements,
11 that the grant will be used to pay a tax lien, delinquent tax, or
12 other obligation owed to this state, or that the grant will create
13 a conflict of interest, the responsible entity shall not release
14 the grant money to the grantee. Money that is not released under
15 this subdivision lapses at the end of the fiscal year. There is not
16 a conflict of interest if the sponsoring legislator certifies that
17 the sponsoring legislator's immediate family members, legislative
18 staff members that have worked for the sponsoring legislator within
19 the past 2 years, and the sponsoring legislator do not have a
20 direct or indirect pecuniary interest in the legislatively directed
21 spending item.
22 (3) An executed grant agreement under this section between the
23 responsible entity and a grant recipient must include at least all
24 of the following:
25 (a) All necessary identifying information for the grant
26 recipient, including any tax and financial information necessary
