26 the next fiscal year, the tuition restraint rate will be adjusted
27 only for the subsequent academic year. As used in this subsection:
28 (a) "Fee" means any board-authorized fee that will be paid by
29 more than 1/2 of all in-district students at least once during
CRM S01533'25 (S-3) CR-1 mposkv

429
1 their enrollment at a community college. A community college
2 increasing a fee that applies to a specific subset of students or
3 courses shall provide sufficient information to prove that the
4 increase applied to that subset will not cause the increase in the
5 average amount of board-authorized total tuition and fees paid by
6 in-district students in the 2024-2025 academic year to exceed the
7 limit established in this section.
8 (b) "Tuition and fee rate" means the average of full-time
9 rates paid by a majority of students in each class, based on an
10 unweighted average of the rates authorized by the community college
11 board and actually charged to students, deducting any uniformly
12 rebated or refunded amounts, for the 2 semesters with the highest
13 levels of full-time equated in-district enrollment during the
14 academic year.
15 (3) Community colleges that exceed the tuition and fee rate
16 cap described in subsection (2) are not eligible to receive
17 payments under section 201 for performance funding or payments
18 under section 201f for 1-time performance funding payments for
19 fiscal year 2024-2025.2025-2026. The state budget director shall
20 implement uniform reporting requirements to ensure that a community
21 college receiving a payment under section 201f for 1-time
22 performance funding has satisfied the tuition restraint
23 requirements of this section. The state budget director has the
24 sole authority to determine if a community college has met the
