3 Sec. 217f. It is the intent of the legislature that taxpayer
4 funds appropriated under this article are to be used to educate
5 community college students and continue maintenance of community
6 college buildings and other assets. The goal of the legislature is
7 that taxpayer funds not be used excessively for administration.
8 Therefore, a community college that receives an appropriation under
9 this article shall not spend more than 10% of that appropriation on
10 administration. A sum of money spent in excess of the 10% cap
11 described in this section by a community college results in a
12 forfeiture of an amount equal to 50% of that sum from funds
13 appropriated to that community college, not to exceed the total
14 amount appropriated to that community college under this article.
15 The auditor general may investigate allegations of violations of
16 this section. Funds forfeited under this section must revert, to
17 the extent permitted by law, to the general fund or the state
18 school aid fund. For the purpose of calculations under this
19 section, the amount spent by a community college on administrative
20 costs does not include costs associated with staff working in the
21 following roles: teachers, facilities, public safety, technology,
22 research, instruction, academic support, student services,
23 auxiliary services, or public service.
24 Sec. 222. Each community college shall have an annual audit of
25 all income and expenditures performed by an independent auditor and
26 shall furnish the independent auditor's management letter and an
27 annual audited accounting of all general and current funds income
28 and expenditures including audits of college foundations to the
29 center before November 15 of each year. The center shall provide
CRM S01533'25 (S-3) CR-1 mposkv

435
1 this information to members of the senate and house appropriations
2 subcommittees on community colleges, the senate and house fiscal
3 agencies, the auditor general, the department of labor and economic
4 opportunity, the department of lifelong education, advancement, and
5 potential, and the state budget director. If a community college
6 fails to furnish the audit materials, the monthly state aid
7 operations installments must be withheld from that college until
8 the information is submitted. All reporting must conform to the
9 requirements set forth in the "2001 Manual for Uniform Financial
10 Reporting, Michigan Public Community Colleges". A community college
11 shall make the information the community college is required to
12 provide under this section available to the public on its website.
